Zumo Robot!¶

In ME480, students program the zumo 32u4 robot to navigate autonomously around a race track while avoiding obstacles. The first step to being able to do this is to develop a model that relates an idealized input voltage from the batteries to the zumo's translational forward speed $v$.

As an ES103 student with knowledge of mechanical systems, electrical systems, and power-converting transducers, you now have the tools to build this model yourself!

Fixed assumptions¶

We may not know everything we need to know, but we do have the following "best guesses" for various properties of various parts of the robot.

  • The zumo's mass is roughly $M=.26kg$ with Duracell batteries according to my kitchen scale.
  • The zumo has two motors: one on the left side, and one on the right side. However, we will attempt to model only half of the zumo using a symmetry argument, and consider only one motor/track and half of the zumo's mass $m = \frac{M}{2}$. Each motor shaft directly drives one of the zumo's front wheels-- the back wheel on each side is simply driven by the track.
  • The zumo's motor has a torque constant of roughly $k_t = 0.05 \frac{Nm}{A}$
  • The zumo's tracks/wheels are very light relative to the inertia of the motor's rotating parts. The wheels with tracks have a radius of approximately $r=0.016m$ according to a ruler.
  • We will assume the Zumo's motor armature (coil) has an electrical resistance of roughly 4 $\Omega$.
  • The zumo's motor shaft and other rotating parts have an effective inertia that is unpublished, but a rough estimate can be provided by your senior mentors; they fit these values as part of ME480!
  • The Zumo's battery provides a roughly constant voltage of $6V$ (4 AA Batteries)
  • The bearings connecting the Zumo's motor shaft to its (non-rotating) outer housing has a damping constant that is unpublished, but a rough estimate can be provided by your senior mentors; they fit these values as part of ME480!

Data for a run where the zumo starts from rest, and receives a sudden constant voltage input from the batteries is included with this notebook as veldata.txt. The first column is time (seconds) and the second is zumo velocity (m/s).

To aid you in model validation, you can use the following code stub, which loads and plots data from a zumo run conducted in Fall 2021. These data are from an actual Zumo robot! The resolution of the Zumo's wheel position sensors (which were used to get velocity) is not great so the data are a bit noisey!!

In [1]:
clear all
data = load('veldata.txt');
t = data(1:end,1);
v = data(1:end,2);

plot(t,v,'k',t,v,'r')
xlabel('time (s)')
ylabel('Velocity (m/s)')
